<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-962-288  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 962 288.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Dec 11 1989 v6 n49 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DEC program lets PDP-11 customers upgrade to MicroVAX.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, Glen.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (customer relations).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Product:   DEC MicroVAX 3000 (Minicomputer) (marketing)DEC PDP-11 (Minicomputer) (marketing).andO;Topic:     UpgradingMinicomputersMarketing StrategyMarket Share.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DEC Program Lets PDP-11 Customers Upgrade to MicroVAXandM;MAYNARD, Mass.andP;  -- DEC has added a new member to its MicroVAX 3000 upgradeprograms--the PDP-11.andM;DEC has announced that until June 30, 1990, customers can upgrade theirPDP-11 systems to MicroVAX 3000-series machines under the company'sMicroMove-Up program.andM;The program is a further attempt by DEC to prevent an erosion of its customerbase, according to John B. Jones Jr., an industry analyst for MontgomerySecurities, a San Francisco-based investment research company.andM;&quot;I think the issue is, if they don't upgrade their old tire irons with theirown products, [the customers] will upgrade with someone else's product, andDEC will lose market share,&quot; Jones said.andM;Last month, DEC announced a board-level upgrade program for MicroVAX II andVAXstation II customers.andM;Prior to the announcement, DEC had required most of its existing customerbase to buy fully configured MicroVAX 3000 systems rather than allowing themto upgrade to the MicroVAX 3000 series by replacing the MicroVAX II CPU.andM;Prices for the PDP-11 upgrade program have not been announced.andO;</TEXT></DOC>